WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en-GB

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.000
Hello!

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:03.680
On Sunday morning, 22nd February 2026,

00:00:03.680 --> 00:00:07.800
no one had imagined that the most wanted drug lord in the world

00:00:07.800 --> 00:00:09.560
would be hiding in a place like this.

00:00:09.560 --> 00:00:12.640
It was Mexico's small, mountainous tourist town,

00:00:12.640 --> 00:00:13.640
Tapalpa.

00:00:17.240 --> 00:00:18.760
There are stone roads,

00:00:18.760 --> 00:00:19.840
tourist shops,

00:00:19.840 --> 00:00:21.080
and green mountains,

00:00:21.080 --> 00:00:24.240
but in the outer area of this beautiful town,

00:00:24.240 --> 00:00:25.440
in the middle of the jungle,

00:00:25.440 --> 00:00:26.960
there was a cabin complex

00:00:26.960 --> 00:00:29.280
where El Mencho was hidden.

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:31.480
The

00:00:31.480 --> 00:00:33.080
The

00:00:33.080 --> 00:00:38.360
El Mencho was the man for whom the US had offered a $15 million reward.

00:00:38.360 --> 00:00:43.360
He was so secretive that only a few photos of him were available.

00:00:43.360 --> 00:00:47.440
He had been arrested in the 1980s and 1990s.

00:00:47.440 --> 00:00:50.600
No one knew what he looked like today.

00:00:50.600 --> 00:00:51.880
But on 20th February,

00:00:51.880 --> 00:00:55.160
Mexican intelligence received an important lead.

00:00:55.160 --> 00:00:58.600
By tracking an associate of El Mencho's romantic partner,

00:00:58.600 --> 00:01:02.540
authorities found that the associate had taken the partner outside Tapalpa

00:01:02.540 --> 00:01:05.220
to a secluded rural property.

00:01:05.220 --> 00:01:08.360
This was the same secret place where El Mencho was hiding.

00:01:10.580 --> 00:01:13.080
On 21st February, his partner left the location,

00:01:13.080 --> 00:01:15.800
but El Mencho stayed behind with his bodyguards.

00:01:15.800 --> 00:01:17.160
They met with El Mencho.

00:01:17.160 --> 00:01:19.400
The couple met with Mencho at that location.

00:01:19.400 --> 00:01:21.160
And on February 21st,

00:01:21.160 --> 00:01:25.000
they left the building, and information was obtained that Mencho was still there.

00:01:28.600 --> 00:01:34.200
The Mexican forces were given the opportunity they had been waiting for for years.

00:01:34.200 --> 00:01:37.080
On 22nd February, before dawn,

00:01:37.080 --> 00:01:41.480
the Mexican special forces, the National Guard, the Air Force, and the Army

00:01:41.480 --> 00:01:44.280
surrounded the compound from all sides.

00:01:44.280 --> 00:01:48.680
Without a doubt, the mission was primarily executed by ground forces.

00:01:48.680 --> 00:01:51.000
Helicopters were used in limited numbers.

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:53.480
As the soldiers advanced toward the compound,

00:01:53.480 --> 00:01:55.480
the cartel's gunmen started firing.

00:01:55.480 --> 00:02:02.440
The security forces shot down four cartel members.

00:02:02.440 --> 00:02:05.640
But El Mencho fled the compound with his bodyguards

00:02:05.640 --> 00:02:09.360
and headed for a wooden cabin complex in a nearby jungle.

00:02:09.360 --> 00:02:13.480
The security forces followed him and opened fire a second time.

00:02:15.060 --> 00:02:18.480
Finally, the soldiers caught El Mencho in serious condition

00:02:18.480 --> 00:02:20.480
along with two bodyguards.

00:02:20.480 --> 00:02:23.480
He was immediately airlifted to Mexico City

00:02:23.480 --> 00:02:26.040
but died on the way.

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:28.600
A former DEA chief

00:02:28.600 --> 00:02:33.640
calls this operation one of the most significant actions in drug trafficking history.

00:02:33.640 --> 00:02:35.480
But the story doesn't end here.

00:02:35.480 --> 00:02:37.000
What happened after his death

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:39.240
was beyond anything one could imagine.

00:02:39.240 --> 00:02:40.840
The death of this drug lord

00:02:40.840 --> 00:02:43.000
set the whole country on fire.

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:44.680
But the question here is,

00:02:44.680 --> 00:02:46.440
who was this El Mencho?

00:02:46.440 --> 00:02:49.800
And how did his cartel become so powerful?

00:02:53.480 --> 00:03:02.840
In 1992, in California,

00:03:02.840 --> 00:03:05.520
the police caught a small-time drug dealer.

00:03:05.520 --> 00:03:07.120
He was dealing in heroin.

00:03:07.120 --> 00:03:09.880
He was sent to jail and later deported.

00:03:09.880 --> 00:03:12.320
But no one thought that this man

00:03:12.320 --> 00:03:16.320
would become the most wanted drug lord in the world twenty years later.

00:03:16.320 --> 00:03:18.960
This story begins in 1966,

00:03:18.960 --> 00:03:22.320
in the city of Aguililla in Michoacán State, Mexico.

00:03:22.320 --> 00:03:25.000
This was an area where poverty was at its peak

00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:28.800
and where illegal marijuana plantations were hidden in the mountains.

00:03:28.800 --> 00:03:32.760
El Mencho was born Nemesio Jose Guerra Cervantes.

00:03:32.760 --> 00:03:35.000
His family were avocado farmers.

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:39.320
He left school in the 5th grade to help his family.

00:03:39.320 --> 00:03:41.200
He started his career in farming.

00:03:41.200 --> 00:03:42.800
But by the time he turned 14,

00:03:42.800 --> 00:03:46.760
he was in charge of marijuana fields.

00:03:46.760 --> 00:03:48.120
In the 1980s,

00:03:48.120 --> 00:03:49.800
in search of a better life,

00:03:49.800 --> 00:03:51.200
he went to America

00:03:51.200 --> 00:03:53.200
and moved to California.

00:03:53.200 --> 00:03:55.960
He had dreamed of the Great American Dream.

00:03:55.960 --> 00:03:57.660
But instead of a better life,

00:03:57.660 --> 00:03:59.880
he found a life of crime in America.

00:04:01.880 --> 00:04:05.680
In 1986, the San Francisco Police arrested him for theft

00:04:05.680 --> 00:04:08.800
and for possession of a loaded gun.

00:04:08.800 --> 00:04:11.520
Officers suspected that he was a meth dealer.

00:04:11.520 --> 00:04:13.840
After a few years of hiding and stealing,

00:04:13.840 --> 00:04:16.820
in 1992, at the San Francisco Imperial Bar,

00:04:16.820 --> 00:04:20.320
undercover cops caught him selling heroin.

00:04:20.320 --> 00:04:22.440
He was sentenced to three years in prison.

00:04:22.440 --> 00:04:24.880
It was in January 1997

00:04:24.880 --> 00:04:27.440
that Mencho was released on parole.

00:04:27.440 --> 00:04:30.240
He was then deported back to Mexico.

00:04:30.240 --> 00:04:32.240
He was 30 years old at the time.

00:04:32.240 --> 00:04:34.920
And this is where the story takes a major twist.

00:04:36.840 --> 00:04:38.280
After returning to Mexico,

00:04:38.280 --> 00:04:40.480
Mencho became a police officer.

00:04:40.480 --> 00:04:41.960
You heard that right.

00:04:41.960 --> 00:04:43.880
A convicted drug dealer

00:04:43.880 --> 00:04:45.400
became a police officer.

00:04:45.400 --> 00:04:47.320
He worked for the police for a few years.

00:04:47.320 --> 00:04:48.160
And during these years,

00:04:48.160 --> 00:04:50.280
he understood the inner workings of the force.

00:04:50.280 --> 00:04:54.760
He understood how easily the Mexican police could be bought with a small amount of money.

00:04:54.760 --> 00:04:56.760
He saw how much an officer would sell his soul for.

00:04:56.760 --> 00:04:59.080
And he saw exactly where the holes in the system were.

00:04:59.080 --> 00:05:03.560
This knowledge was going to become one of his most dangerous weapons.

00:05:03.560 --> 00:05:07.320
During this time, he married Rosalinda Gonzalez Valencia,

00:05:07.320 --> 00:05:10.200
a woman who came from a powerful cartel family.

00:05:10.200 --> 00:05:14.040
This marriage became his entry ticket into organized crime.

00:05:14.040 --> 00:05:18.280
In the beginning, he became a bodyguard and hitman for the Valencia family's Milenio Cartel.

00:05:18.280 --> 00:05:25.080
But by 2010, all the leaders of that cartel were either killed or in jail.

00:05:25.080 --> 00:05:27.620
Mencho asked for leadership, but he didn't get it.

00:05:27.620 --> 00:05:30.420
So he broke away and formed his own group.

00:05:30.420 --> 00:05:43.184
He founded the Cártel de Jalisco Nueva Generación, or CJNG. Fast forward five years later to 1st May 2015, the Mexican military launched Operation Jalisco to capture El Mencho.

00:05:43.184 --> 00:05:45.344
Military helicopters were used,

00:05:45.344 --> 00:05:47.864
but the CJNG already knew about it.

00:05:47.864 --> 00:05:52.744
Cartel gunmen were armed with RPG-27 rocket launchers and heavy machine guns.

00:05:52.744 --> 00:05:55.224
When helicopters arrived to attack the cartel,

00:05:55.224 --> 00:05:59.464
they used those rocket launchers and machine guns to shoot them down.

00:06:00.464 --> 00:06:05.564
We heard a boom like a bomb. They took down the aircraft. They shot it down.

00:06:05.564 --> 00:06:08.384
Only 9 out of 18 people survived.

00:06:08.384 --> 00:06:09.824
Even those were seriously wounded.

00:06:09.824 --> 00:06:14.224
Think about it, a drug cartel shot down a military helicopter.

00:06:14.224 --> 00:06:18.384
This cartel was so powerful that later on, in different areas of Mexico,

00:06:18.384 --> 00:06:21.824
they set fire to dozens of buses, trucks, and gas stations.

00:06:21.824 --> 00:06:25.824
The Mexican government had to send 10,000 troops to control the situation.

00:06:25.824 --> 00:06:29.104
A federal investigator even said that since the time of Pablo Escobar,

00:06:29.104 --> 00:06:33.545
a drug mafia had never had such a direct and violent confrontation with the authorities.

00:06:33.545 --> 00:06:34.304
Thank you.

00:06:34.304 --> 00:06:35.424
You are the power of the world.

00:06:35.424 --> 00:06:36.545
Yes, you are the power of the world.

00:06:36.545 --> 00:06:41.344
But the question is, how did this CJNG become so powerful?

00:06:41.344 --> 00:06:43.184
The answer lies in two chemicals:

00:06:43.184 --> 00:06:45.664
Methamphetamine and fentanyl.

00:06:45.664 --> 00:06:48.545
CJNG was not an ordinary drug cartel.

00:06:48.545 --> 00:06:51.104
It operated like a paramilitary force.

00:06:51.104 --> 00:06:52.904
According to DEA estimates,

00:06:52.904 --> 00:06:56.624
of all the drugs entering America by air and sea in 2019,

00:06:56.624 --> 00:07:00.624
at least one-third belonged to this single cartel.

00:07:00.624 --> 00:07:05.505
By 2018, CJNG had more than 100 meth labs in Mexico.

00:07:05.505 --> 00:07:09.664
The profit margins for meth were many times higher than those for cocaine and heroin.

00:07:09.664 --> 00:07:11.104
And most importantly,

00:07:11.104 --> 00:07:14.624
while Colombian suppliers had to depend on coca plants,

00:07:14.624 --> 00:07:17.744
meth could be manufactured independently

00:07:17.744 --> 00:07:19.664
by importing chemicals from China.

00:07:19.664 --> 00:07:24.704
Some experts estimate that CJNG's war chest was worth more than $20 billion.

00:07:24.704 --> 00:07:26.704
The entire port system of Mexico,

00:07:26.704 --> 00:07:27.984
specifically the Port of Manzanillo,

00:07:27.984 --> 00:07:29.744
was under the control of this cartel.

00:07:29.744 --> 00:07:32.984
The raw materials imported from China through this port

00:07:32.984 --> 00:07:34.304
were used to manufacture meth.

00:07:34.304 --> 00:07:36.505
There is an interesting pattern in this story.

00:07:36.505 --> 00:07:39.584
CJNG controlled the Port of Manzanillo

00:07:39.584 --> 00:07:43.024
because everything was available from a single access point.

00:07:43.024 --> 00:07:45.144
Chemicals, logistics, and the supply chain

00:07:45.144 --> 00:07:46.384
were all in one place.

